      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      There are two methods for finding the vertex form from the standard form.
      The first one uses completing the square to accomplish the transformation.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="completing-the-square-to-vertex-form">
      <title>Using Completing the Square to Convert from Standard to Vertex Form</title>

      <statement>
        <p>Convert <m>f(x) = 3x^2 - 12x + 13</m> to vertex form.</p>
      </statement>

      <solution><p>
<md>
  <mrow>f(x)\amp= 3x^2 - 12x + 13 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>f(x) - 13\amp= 3x^2 - 12x \\</mrow>
  <mrow>\frac{f(x)}{3} - \frac{13}{3}\amp= \frac{3x^2}{3} - \frac{12}{3}x \\</mrow>
  <mrow>\frac{f(x)}{3} - \frac{13}{3}\amp= x^2 - 4x \\</mrow>
  <mrow>\frac{f(x)}{3} - \frac{13}{3}\amp= x^2 - 4x \amp \frac{-4}{2}\amp= -2 \amp (-2)^2\amp= 4 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>\frac{f(x)}{3} - \frac{13}{3} + 4\amp= x^2 - 4x + 4 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>\frac{f(x)}{3} - \frac{13}{3} + 4\amp= (x - 2)^2 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>3\left(\frac{f(x)}{3}\right) - 3\left(\frac{13}{3}\right) + 3(4)\amp= 3(x - 2)^2 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>f(x) - 13 + 12\amp= 3(x - 2)^2 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>f(x) - 1\amp= 3(x - 2)^2 \\</mrow>
  <mrow>f(x)\amp= 3(x - 2)^2 + 1</mrow>
</md>
</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </subsection>
</section>
